<h3>Middleman is a static site generator.</h3> 

<p>This just means that rather than you 
manually writing each line of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, the tool writes some 
of them for you based on the source you provide. Perhaps you want to write your 
pages in Markdown, or your CSS using SASS. Perhaps you want to avoid 
duplication by applying a common layout to all pages. Perhaps you want to write 
articles as simple text files and have them compiled into a working blog. 
Static site generators can do these kinds of things for you, spitting out plain 
old HTML, CSS, and JavaScript that you can host on any cheap web server.</p>

<p>That last bit is important. <strong>Your static site should be plain HTML, CSS, and 
JavaScript.</strong> I&#39;ve seen plenty of static sites built with Rails or Sinatra. It 
makes sense from a developer workflow standpoint -- these tools are wonderful 
to work with -- but it makes no sense from a deployment standpoint. Since there 
is no database layer or framework code, static sites will always be more 
secure, performant, and portable. Your site will fly, and hosting will be cheap 
or free.</p>

