<p>Perhaps one of the best-known static site generators is 
<a href="https://github.com/mojombo/jekyll">Jekyll</a>. It&#39;s been around a while and is an 
excellent blogging platform. <strong>Think of Middleman as Jekyll on steroids.</strong> 
While blogging isn&#39;t front-and-center on the Middleman site, blogging is 
<a href="http://middlemanapp.com/blogging/">well-supported and documented</a>.</p>

<h3>Middleman embraces Rails conventions.</h3> 

<p>Many of the functions of a static 
site generator are already handled by web application frameworks like Rails. 
<mark>Why reinvent the wheel and make me learn a new way of doing the same thing?</mark> 
Middleman pulls in the best bits of the Rails front end. The Rails asset 
pipeline is brought in to handle CSS and JavaScript dependencies, 
concatination, minification, and compilation of SASS, CoffeeScript, and more. 
It mimics the Rails template engine to handle partials, layouts, and whatever 
template language you prefer (HAML, Slim, etc.). It also pulls in many Rails 
view helpers for even more convenience. If you&#39;ve ever built a Rails app, 
you&#39;ll be right at home with Middleman.</p>

<h3>Middleman is powerful and extensible.</h3> 

<p>A &quot;static site&quot; in this context is 
really a misnomer. Middleman is perfect for building interactive and dynamic 
client-side apps, too. If I&#39;d known about Middleman when we built 
<a href="http://iwitness.adaptivepath.com">iWitness</a>, a complex client-side Ember app, 
it would&#39;ve saved us <a href="https://github.com/adaptivepath/iWitness/commits/master/Rakefile">tons of 
time</a> we 
spent writing our own build process.  Also, since Middleman is just a Ruby gem, 
it&#39;s easily extendable for things such as <a href="https://github.com/middleman/middleman-smusher">image 
compression</a>, <a href="https://github.com/middleman/middleman-syntax">syntax 
highlighting</a>, and 
<a href="http://middlemanapp.com/community/3rd-party-extensions/">more</a>.</p>

