<p>When it comes time to deploy your Middleman site -- or any static site for that 
matter -- you have endless options. Any web host in the world can host a static 
site. You can even host it on 
<a href="http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/dev/WebsiteHosting.html">S3</a>. The 
winner, though, is <a href="http://pages.github.com">Github Pages</a>. It&#39;s completely 
free, fast, and it integrates with Github, which you probably already use.</p>

<p>Middleman doesn&#39;t come with baked-in deployment options, which is why I created 
the <a href="https://github.com/neo/middleman-gh-pages">middleman-gh-pages</a> gem. It 
adds rake tasks so that <strong>you can deploy your site quickly with a single 
command.</strong> Seriously. Assuming your project repository is already on Github, a 
simple <code class="prettyprint">rake publish</code> is all it takes to publish your work to Github Pages.</p>

<p>I spend most of my time building web apps with <a href="http://rubyonrails.org">Rails</a> 
and deploying these apps to <a href="http://www.heroku.com">Heroku</a>. This tandem makes 
it ridiculously easy to get apps built and deployed quickly. I&#39;ve been spoiled, 
and I expect the same royal treatment when building a static site. I&#39;ve spent 
some time hunting down the static site equivalent of the Rails + Heroku Dream 
Team, and this is it. If you desire the same, Middleman and Github Pages won&#39;t 
let you down.</p>